Prediction Analysis (Logistic Regression)

Author: Cisco EDS
Created: July 18, 2016

Overview¶

The predictive model will publish a risk score that is categorized into low, medium and high buckets. The risk score signifies the probability of issuing an RMA that is avoidable. The main objective behind this is to enable the TAC engineer to be more proactive in identifying and dealing with a case where there is a high chance of issuing the wrong RMA.

Model includes various static & dynamic variables to predict risk score.Static variables are more relevant at the SR Creation time whereas the dynamic variables get populated during the SR journey.

For the analysis we have considered the following conditions:

  1. Time Period = FY15 and FY16
  2. Incident Type = TAC Cases
  3. Only Order lines (without Cancelled and Undispatched orders) has been considered
  4. Only Closed Cases have been considered
  5. % avoidability of cases (with or without RMA) is 7.7%

Data Transformation¶

Loading the DataSet¶

The dataset consists of 250,536 closed cases over the past two financial years for the UCS product family. ~87k cases out of these have atleast one RMA. These cases have been tagged as avoidable or non-avoidable by Fuzzy, RT and rules. The remaining cases that have no RMA issued are considered as non-avoidable for the training dataset. Intuition behind this being, the model has to learn and should be able to publish a low risk score to these kind of cases where there was no RMA issued.

In [2]:
ADS = pd.read_csv("pm_0825.csv", low_memory=False)
TestData  = pd.read_csv("example.csv")

Clean the ARMA column¶

Changing all the NAs in the 'avoidability' column to '0's. These NAs are the cases which have no RMA and since we are considering these cases as non-avoidable, we will have to modify the arma column.

ADS = ADS[ADS['closed_date'] != 'null']

df.arma = df.arma.fillna(0)
dft = TestData.copy()

Modules¶

Making the code modular so that there is no redudant code anywhere in the analysis. Since this analysis is done on almost ~45 variables, there is bound to be a lot of code that is pretty common across all the variables specially in regards to the univariate and bivariate analysis and plotting graphs. Also the idea is to make it very generic so that addition of variables will be easier.

In [4]:
class Categorical():
    def __init__(self,data,testdata):
        self.data = data
        self.testdata = testdata
        self.var = list()

    def Bivariate(self,variable):
        self.df = pd.DataFrame()
        self.data[variable] = self.data[variable].fillna('Unknown')
        self.df = pd.crosstab(self.data[variable],self.data.arma.astype(bool))
        self.df.rename(columns={False : 'NonAvoidable', True : 'Avoidable', 'All' : 'Total'}, inplace=True)
        self.df['%avoidability'] = ((self.df['Avoidable'])/(self.df['NonAvoidable'] + self.df['Avoidable']))*100
        self.df['%avoidability'] = self.df['%avoidability'].round(1)
        self.df['Total']=100
        self.df['Total_cases'] = self.df['NonAvoidable'] + self.df['Avoidable']
        self.df['Total_cases']
        self.df['% Cases'] = self.df['Total_cases']/244294
        self.df['% Cases'] = self.df['% Cases'].round(2)
        self.df = self.df.sort_values(by = '%avoidability',ascending= False ,axis = 0)
        self.df = self.df.reset_index()
        self.df.index.names = ['index']
        print(self.df[[variable,'Total_cases','% Cases','Avoidable','%avoidability']].head(10))
        
    def BivariateNP(self,variable):
        self.df = pd.DataFrame()
        self.data[variable] = self.data[variable].fillna('Unknown')
        self.df = pd.crosstab(self.data[variable],self.data.arma.astype(bool))
        self.df.rename(columns={False : 'NonAvoidable', True : 'Avoidable', 'All' : 'Total'}, inplace=True)
        self.df['%avoidability'] = ((self.df['Avoidable'])/(self.df['NonAvoidable'] + self.df['Avoidable']))*100
        self.df['%avoidability'] = self.df['%avoidability'].round(1)
        self.df['Total']=100
        self.df['Total_cases'] = self.df['NonAvoidable'] + self.df['Avoidable']
        self.df['% Cases'] = self.df['Total_cases']/2442.94
        self.df['% Cases'] = self.df['% Cases'].round(2)
        self.df = self.df.sort_values(by = '%avoidability',ascending= False ,axis = 0)
        self.df = self.df.reset_index()
        self.df.index.names = ['index']
        
    def Bivariate2(self,variable):
        self.df = pd.DataFrame()
        self.data[variable] = self.data[variable].fillna('Unknown')
        self.df = pd.crosstab(self.data[variable],self.data.arma.astype(bool))
        self.df.rename(columns={False : 'NonAvoidable', True : 'Avoidable', 'All' : 'Total'}, inplace=True)
        self.df['%avoidability'] = ((self.df['Avoidable'])/(self.df['NonAvoidable'] + self.df['Avoidable']))*100
        self.df['%avoidability'] = self.df['%avoidability'].round(1)
        self.df['Total']=100
        self.df['Total_cases'] = self.df['NonAvoidable'] + self.df['Avoidable']
        self.df['% Cases'] = self.df['Total_cases']/2442.94
        self.df['% Cases'] = self.df['% Cases'].round(2)
        self.df = self.df.sort_values(by = 'Total_cases',ascending= False ,axis = 0)
        self.df = self.df.reset_index()
        print (self.df[[variable,'Total_cases','% Cases','Avoidable','%avoidability']].head(20))
        
    
    def changetocat(self,variable):
        self.df[variable] = self.df[variable].astype('category')

    def Graph(self,variable):
        self.var.append(variable)
        f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 5))
        sns.set_color_codes("pastel")
        sns.barplot(x="Total", y=variable, data=self.df, color="b")
        sns.set_color_codes("muted")
        sns.barplot(x="%avoidability", y=variable, data=self.df,label="avoidability", color="b")

        # Add a legend and informative axis label
        ax.legend(ncol=2, loc="lower right", frameon=True)
        ax.set(xlim=(0, 100), ylabel="", xlabel="percentage")
        sns.despine(left=True, bottom=True)

        
    def Bucketing(self,variable):
        bins = [0,5,9,13,17,21,25,29,33,37,41,45,49,53,57,61,65,69,73,77,81,85,89,93,97,100]
        levels = ['_level0','_level1','_level2','_level3','_level4','_level5','_level6','_level7','_level8','_level9','_level10','_level11','_level12',
         '_level13','_level14','_level15','_level16','_level17','_level18','_level19','_level20','_level21','_level22','_level23','_level24',
         '_level25','_level26']

        self.df['capturemap'] = pd.cut(self.df['%avoidability'],bins,include_lowest = True)
        self.mapping = pd.Series(self.df['capturemap'].values,index=self.df[variable]).to_dict()
        
        self.df[variable] = pd.cut(self.df['%avoidability'],bins,include_lowest = True)

        self.maps = dict(zip(list(self.df[variable].unique()),levels))
        
        self.df[variable] = self.df[variable].astype('object')

        self.df[variable] = self.df[variable].map(lambda x: variable + self.maps[x])
                
        self.df = self.df.groupby(variable).sum()[['NonAvoidable','Avoidable']].reset_index()
        self.df['%avoidability'] = ((self.df['Avoidable'])/(self.df['NonAvoidable'] + self.df['Avoidable']))*100
        self.df['%avoidability'] = self.df['%avoidability'].round(1)
        self.df['Total'] = 100
        self.df[variable] = self.df[variable].astype('category')
    
    def MasterSetbucketing(self,variable):
        self.data[variable] = self.data[variable].map(lambda x: variable + self.maps[self.mapping[x]])
        
    def TestSetbucketing(self,variable):
        self.testdata[variable] = self.testdata[variable].map(lambda x: variable + self.maps[self.mapping[x]])
    
    def Gettestdata(self):
        return self.testdata
    
    def Dummyvalues(self, variable):
        pd.get_dummies(self.df)
        pd.get_dummies(self.df).columns
        
    def Getdata(self):
        return self.data
    
    def Getvariables(self):
        return self.var
       
    def Collinearity(self):
        pass

Missing Value and Outlier Treatment¶

  1. Categorical Variables: All the missing values have been replaced by 'Unknown'. Outlier Treatment is not required for the categorical variables

  2. Continuous Variables : We do not have missing values for any of the continuous variables. All the records above x percentile are removed as a result of the outlier treatment

Bucketing¶

There are various categorical variables (Customer Name, Country, Customer_vertical, Customer_Market_segment, etc) wih more than 100 levels. We need to reduce the # of levels by bucketing them based on the response rate (% avoidability). The reason behind reducing the levels is to avoid overfitting of the model and also make the process of flushing out the insignificant variables easier.

Bucketing is done on the basis of frequency(% Cases) and the response rate(% Avoidability). If the response rate for the fields is similar across the fields with %Cases < 5%, they can be grouped as into a single field

Var 1 : Entry Channel (Static)¶

  • Description : Channel through which the customer raised the SR
  • Hypothesis : There is a higher risk of cases having Avoidable RMA if the entry channel used to raise the request is 'Automatic'
  • Findings :
    • Cases raised through Automatic channel have highest % avoidability(14.9%) which is 92% more than the avg %avoidability(7.7%)
    • 93% of the cases were raised through 'Web' channel

class Continuous():
    def __init__(self,data):
        self.data = data
        self.varc = list()

    def Bivariate(self,variable):
        self.df = pd.DataFrame()
        self.data[variable].fillna(df[variable].mean(), inplace = True)        # fill missing values
        self.df = pd.crosstab(self.data[variable],self.data.arma.astype(bool))
        self.df.rename(columns={False : 'NonAvoidable', True : 'Avoidable', 'All' : 'Total'}, inplace=True)
        self.df['%avoidability'] = ((self.df['Avoidable'])/(self.df['NonAvoidable'] + self.df['Avoidable']))*100
        self.df['%avoidability'] = self.df['%avoidability'].round(1)
        self.df['Total'] = 100
        self.df['Total_cases']= self.df['NonAvoidable'] + self.df['Avoidable']
        self.df['% Cases']= self.df['Total_cases']/2442.94
        self.df = self.df.sort_values(by = '%avoidability' , axis = 0)
        self.df = self.df.reset_index()
        print(self.df[[variable,'Total_cases','% Cases','%avoidability']])
        
    def Bivariate2(self,variable):
        self.df = pd.DataFrame()
        self.data[variable].fillna(df[variable].mean(), inplace = True)        # fill missing values
        self.df = pd.crosstab(self.data[variable],self.data.arma.astype(bool))
        self.df.rename(columns={False : 'NonAvoidable', True : 'Avoidable', 'All' : 'Total'}, inplace=True)
        self.df['%avoidability'] = ((self.df['Avoidable'])/(self.df['NonAvoidable'] + self.df['Avoidable']))*100
        self.df['%avoidability'] = self.df['%avoidability'].round(1)
        self.df['Total'] = 100
        self.df['Total_cases']=self.df['NonAvoidable'] + self.df['Avoidable']
        self.df['% Cases']=self.df['Total_cases']/2442.94
        self.df = self.df.sort_values(by = '%avoidability', ascending = False , axis = 0)
        self.df = self.df.reset_index()
        print(self.df[[variable,'Total_cases','% Cases','%avoidability']].head(20))

    def Graph(self,variable):
        self.varc.append(variable)
        sns.set_style("ticks")
        sns.lmplot(variable, '%avoidability', data=self.df, fit_reg=False,scatter_kws={"marker": "D", 
                        "s": 100})
        plt.title(variable + ' vs %avoidability')
        plt.xlabel(variable)
        plt.ylabel('%avoidability')
        
    def Getdata(self):
        return self.data
    
    def Getvariables(self):
        return self.varc

    def Collinearity(self):
        pass

class modelrun():
    def __init__(self,data,var,varc):
        self.data = data
        self.variables = var.copy()
        self.variablesc = varc.copy()
        self.variablesc.append('arma')
        
    def createdummycolumns(self):
        self.moddata = self.data.copy()
        for var in self.variables:
            dummy_ranks = pd.get_dummies(self.data[var],prefix = var)
            self.moddata = self.moddata[self.variablesc].join(dummy_ranks.ix[:, : -1])
            self.variablesc = self.moddata.columns.values
        
    def createtestdummycolumns(self):
        self.moddata = self.data.copy()
        for var in self.variables:
            dummy_ranks = pd.get_dummies(self.data[var],prefix = var)
            self.moddata = self.moddata[self.variablesc].join(dummy_ranks)
            self.variablesc = self.moddata.columns.values
    
    def gettrainingcols(self):
        return self.train_cols

    def run(self):
        logit = sm.Logit(self.moddata['arma'], self.moddata[self.train_cols])
        self.result = logit.fit_regularized(method = 'l1')
        return self.result

    def PredictTest(self,result,train_cols):
        self.moddata = self.moddata.reset_index()
        for col in train_cols:
            if col not in self.moddata.columns:
                self.moddata[col] = 0
        predicted = result.predict(self.moddata[train_cols])
        return predicted
    
    def kcross(self):

        for train_index,test_index in kf:
            logit = sm.Logit(self.moddata['arma'].ix[train_index.tolist()], self.moddata[self.train_cols].ix[train_index.tolist()])
            result = logit.fit_regularized(method = 'l1')   
            predicted = result.predict(self.moddata[self.train_cols].ix[test_index.tolist()])
            actual = self.moddata['arma'].ix[test_index.tolist()]
            pa = pd.DataFrame(list(predicted),list(actual)).reset_index()
            pa = pa.rename(columns = {'index' : 'Actual', 0 : 'Probability'})
            pa['Predicted'] = np.where(pa['Probability'] >= 0.1,1,0)
            pa = pa.astype('int64')
            C = confusion_matrix(pa['Actual'], pa['Predicted'])
            count = count + 1
            assert C.shape == (2,2), "Confusion matrix should be from binary classification only."
            tn = C[0,0]; fp = C[0,1]; fn = C[1,0]; tp = C[1,1];
            self.pred=pd.DataFrame()
            PreValue = round(((tp)/(tp+fn))*100,2)
            ActValue = round((tp+tn)/(fp+tn+tp+fn)*100,2)
            display("Iteration " + str(count) + " : ")
            display("Positive Prediction" + " : " + str(PreValue) + " %")
            display("Actual Prediction" + " : " + str(ActValue) +  " %")
            self.show_confusion_matrix(C)

    def show_confusion_matrix(self,C,class_labels=['0','1']): 
        assert C.shape == (2,2), "Confusion matrix should be from binary classification only."
        # true negative, false positive, etc...
        tn = C[0,0]; fp = C[0,1]; fn = C[1,0]; tp = C[1,1];
        NP = fn+tp # Num positive examples
        NN = tn+fp # Num negative examples
        N  = NP+NN
        fig = plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
        ax  = fig.add_subplot(111)
        ax.imshow(C, interpolation='nearest', cmap=plt.cm.gray)

        # Draw the grid boxes
        ax.set_xlim(-0.5,2.5)
        ax.set_ylim(2.5,-0.5)
        ax.plot([-0.5,2.5],[0.5,0.5], '-k', lw=2)
        ax.plot([-0.5,2.5],[1.5,1.5], '-k', lw=2)
        ax.plot([0.5,0.5],[-0.5,2.5], '-k', lw=2)
        ax.plot([1.5,1.5],[-0.5,2.5], '-k', lw=2)

        # Set xlabels
        ax.set_xlabel('Predicted Label', fontsize=16)
        ax.set_xticks([0,1,2])
        ax.set_xticklabels(class_labels + [''])
        ax.xaxis.set_label_position('top')
        ax.xaxis.tick_top()
        # These coordinate might require some tinkering. Ditto for y, below.
        ax.xaxis.set_label_coords(0.34,1.06)

        # Set ylabels
        ax.set_ylabel('True Label', fontsize=16, rotation=90)
        ax.set_yticklabels(class_labels + [''],rotation=90)
        ax.set_yticks([0,1,2])
        ax.yaxis.set_label_coords(-0.09,0.65)

        # Fill in initial metrics: tp, tn, etc...
        ax.text(0,0,'True Neg: %d\n(Num Neg: %d)'%(tn,NN),va='center',ha='center',bbox=dict(fc='w',boxstyle='round,pad=1'))
        ax.text(0,1,'False Neg: %d'%fn,va='center',ha='center',bbox=dict(fc='w',boxstyle='round,pad=1'))
        ax.text(1,0,'False Pos: %d'%fp,va='center',ha='center',bbox=dict(fc='w',boxstyle='round,pad=1'))
        ax.text(1,1,'True Pos: %d\n(Num Pos: %d)'%(tp,NP),va='center',ha='center',bbox=dict(fc='w',boxstyle='round,pad=1'))
        # Fill in secondary metrics: accuracy, true pos rate, etc...
        ax.text(2,0,'False Pos Rate: %.2f'%(fp / (fp+tn+0.)),va='center',ha='center',bbox=dict(fc='w',boxstyle='round,pad=1'))
        ax.text(2,1,'True Pos Rate: %.2f'%(tp / (tp+fn+0.)),va='center',ha='center',bbox=dict(fc='w',boxstyle='round,pad=1'))
        ax.text(2,2,'Accuracy: %.2f'%((tp+tn+0.)/N),va='center',ha='center',bbox=dict(fc='w',boxstyle='round,pad=1'))
        ax.text(0,2,'Neg Pre Val: %.2f'%(1-fn/(fn+tn+0.)),va='center',ha='center',bbox=dict(fc='w',boxstyle='round,pad=1'))
        ax.text(1,2,'Pos Pred Val: %.2f'%(tp/(tp+fn+0.)),va='center',ha='center',bbox=dict(fc='w',boxstyle='round,pad=1'))
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()
        
        #print the postive prediction and actual prediction
        self.pred=pd.DataFrame()
        self.pred['Positive Prediction'] = tp/(fp+fn)
        self.pred['Actual Prediction'] = (tp+fn)/(fp+tn+tp+fn)
        return(self.pred)

    def getprob(self):
        logit = sm.Logit(self.moddata['arma'], self.moddata[self.train_cols])
        result = logit.fit_regularized(method = 'l1')
        probability=result.predict(self.moddata[self.train_cols])
        pr = pd.DataFrame()
        pr['probability']=list(probability)
        pr['incident_number']=self.data['incident_number']
        pr['arma']=self.data['arma']
        pr = pr.sort_values(by = 'probability' ,axis = 0).reset_index()
        return pr

    def getROC(self):
        count = 0
        kf = KFold(244294,n_folds = 10)
        self.moddata = self.moddata.reset_index()
        for train_index,test_index in kf:
            logit = sm.Logit(self.moddata['arma'].ix[train_index.tolist()], self.moddata[self.train_cols].ix[train_index.tolist()])
            result = logit.fit_regularized(method = 'l1')   
            predicted = result.predict(self.moddata[self.train_cols].ix[test_index.tolist()])
            actual = self.moddata['arma'].ix[test_index.tolist()]
            pa = pd.DataFrame(list(predicted),list(actual)).reset_index()
            pa = pa.rename(columns = {'index' : 'Actual', 0 : 'Probability'})
            return pa

Summary¶

Accuracy - The accuracy of the model is around 87%. Inferred from the various cross validation tests performed below. Please take a look at the confusion matrices for more information

Positive predictive power - The positive predictive rate is about 84%. This means that the model predicts the cases with avoidable RMAs correctly 70% of the times

Psuedo R-Square : A value of rho squared (Mcfadden's r square) signifies the goodness of fit for the model. Psuedo r-square or Mcfadden's r square is not to be confused with the traditional r square in the OLS models. By rule of thumb, any value between 0.1 and 0.4 is supposed to be a good fit and anything greater than 0.4 is considered to be a great fit

Log-Likelihood & Log null : Log likelihood will give you the significance of a model fit relative to the Log null. The value against Log - likelihood as such doesn't mean a lot, it should be compared to the log null value. Log null value is the fit with no predictors. The increase in the value(log likelihood) will signify how much of an impact the predictor variables have on the model.

Intrepreting the Coefficients against each variable (Odds Ratio) : The coefficients of the variables in itself do not mean anything and they make sense only when the exponential of this coefficient is taken. For ex - The odds ratio for engineer count is 1.7, this means that the odds of being avoidable increase by 70% for every engineer added to the case

  • Total number of variables = 69
  • Number of variables with positive B-coefficient = 36
  • Number of variables with positive B-coefficient = 33

10 fold Cross validation¶

The cross validation has been done 10 times by taking the random sample of 10% of the dataset each time. We have calculated the Positive prediction(i.e. Number of times the the model predicted 1 out of the actual 1s) and Actual prediction(.i.e Number of times the model predicted true positives or true negatives out of all the predictions).

  • The Positive Prediction is in the range of 83% - 89%
  • The Actual Prediction is in the range of 84% - 87%

Since the Positive Prediction and the Actual Prediction fall in the similar range in the 10 crossvalidations, the model is stable

def Find_Optimal_Cutoff(target, predicted):
    fpr, tpr, threshold = metrics.roc_curve(target, predicted)
    i = np.arange(len(tpr)) 
    roc = pd.DataFrame({'tf' : pd.Series(tpr-(1-fpr), index=i), 'threshold' : pd.Series(threshold, index=i)})
    roc_t = roc.ix[(roc.tf-0).abs().argsort()[:1]]

    return list(roc_t['threshold'])
